      "writtenOn": "2026-04-19T05:48:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Each property has its own nullptr guard:\n- ceCount guard: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/87169/12/redfish-core/lib/memory_metrics.hpp#59\n- ueCount guard: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/87169/12/redfish-core/lib/memory_metrics.hpp#65\nWhen `unpackPropertiesNoThrow` leaves a pointer as null (property absent from the D-Bus reply or type mismatch), the corresponding Redfish field is skipped — no default 0 is exposed.\n\nBoth properties come from the same `xyz.openbmc_project.Memory.MemoryECC` interface, so in the common cases either both are present (populated) or both are absent. The both-absent case is actually caught earlier by the EBADR branch at https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/87169/12/redfish-core/lib/memory_metrics.hpp#37 before reaching here. Partial presence would only happen if a producer registered the interface but omitted one property, which the per-property guards (https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/87169/12/redfish-core/lib/memory_metrics.hpp#59, https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/87169/12/redfish-core/lib/memory_metrics.hpp#65) still handle safely.",
      "parentUuid": "3ebf9284_df746d26",
      "revId": "197e30f3fb596bca51fc2fa380ffa41ec075104d",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
